1. Statistical learning methods

For each of parts (a) through (d), indicate whether we would generally expect the performance of a flexible statistical learning method to be better or worse than an inflexible method. Justify your answer

(a) The number of predictors p is extremely large, and the number of observations n is small.

An inflexible statistical model would be better for this problem. An inflexible model will keep the variance lower than a flexible model and there is less chance of overfitting with an inflexible model since the number of observations is low.

(b) The sample size n is extremely large, and the number of predictors p is small.

A flexible model would work better in this scenario. Since there are a large number of observations, we do not have to worry as much about high variance and a flexible model usually reduces bias. The large sample size allows less chance of us overfitting the model.

(c) The relationship between the predictors and response is highly non-linear.

A flexible model since the relationship is non-linear. It will also provide us with more accurate estimates.

(d) The standard deviation of the error terms, i.e. _ = sd("), is extremely high.

An inflexible model would work better here. The flexible model will capture the high variances of all the data points potentially giving us less accurate estimates. High standard deviation could also potentially mean outliers/noise in the data set which the flexible model will take into account.

2. Bayes’ Rule

Given a dataset including 20 observations (S_1, …. S_20) about the temperature (i.e. hot or cool) for playing golf (i.e. yes or no), you are required to use the Bayes’ rule to calculate by hand the probability of playing golf according to the temperature, i.e. P(Play Golf | Temperature).

S_1 S_2 S_3 S_4 S_5 S_6 S_7 S_8 S_9 S_10
Temperature cool hot hot hot cool cool hot cool hot hot
Play Golf yes no yes no yes yes no yes no yes
S_11 S_12 S_13 S_14 S_15 S_16 S_17 S_18 S_19 S_20
Temperature hot hot hot cool hot hot cool cool cool hot
Play Golf no no yes no no no yes no no no

P(Temp = hot) = 12/20 = 0.6

P(Temp = cool) = 8/20 = 0.4

P(Golf = yes) = 8/20 = 0.4

P(Golf = no) = 12/20 = 0.6

P(hot | yes) = 3/8 = 0.375

P(cool | yes) = 5/8 = 0.625

P(hot | no) = 9/12 = 0.75

P(cool | no) = 3/12 = 0.25

P(Golf|Temp) = P(Temp|Golf)P(Golf)/P(Temp)

True positive => P(yes | hot) = (0.375 x 0.4)/0.6 = 0.25

False negative => P(yes | cool) = (0.625 x 0.4)/0.4 = 0.625

False positive => P(no | hot) = (0.75 x x0.6)/0.6 = 0.75

True negative => P(no | cool) = (0.25 x 0.6)/0.4 = 0.375

(b) Conduct a 10-fold cross validation to evaluate the predictive accuracy of a logistic regression model that uses Temperature as the only predictor. Report the average accuracy and AUROC value obtained over the 10-fold cross validation. Set the value of random seed as “100” when generating fold indices.Consider the predictive label equals to 1, if the predictive probability is greater than 0.5.

library(caret)
library(ROCR)
accuracy_value <- as.numeric()
auroc_value_temp <- as.numeric()
set.seed(100)
training_folds <- createFolds(y=training_set[,6],k=10)

for(i in 1:10){
    fold_cv_train <- training_set[training_folds[[i]],] 
    fold_cv_test <- training_set[-training_folds[[i]],]
    trained_model_temp <- glm(Occupancy  ~ Temperature, data = fold_cv_train, family = binomial)
    pred_prob_temp <- predict(trained_model_temp, fold_cv_test, type='response')
    
    glm.pred <- rep(1,dim(fold_cv_test)[1])
    glm.pred[pred_prob_temp<.5] <- 0
    
    accuracy_fold <- mean(glm.pred == fold_cv_test$Occupancy)
    accuracy_value <- append(accuracy_value, accuracy_fold)

    pr_temp <- prediction(pred_prob_temp, fold_cv_test$Occupancy)
    auroc_temp <- performance(pr_temp, measure = "auc")
    auroc_temp <- auroc_temp@y.values[[1]]
    auroc_value_temp<- append(auroc_value_temp,auroc_temp)
    
}
cat('average accuracy value: ', mean(accuracy_value))
average accuracy value:  0.8411667
cat('average AUROC value: ', mean(auroc_value_temp))
average AUROC value:  0.8695995

(d) Conduct a 10-fold cross validation to evaluate the predictive accuracy of a logistic regression model that uses Temperature and HumidityRatio in the training dataset. Report the average accuracy and AUROC value obtained over the 10-fold cross validation. Set the value of random seed as “100” when generating fold indices. Consider the predictive label equals to 1, if the predictive probability is greater than 0.5.

accuracy_value <- as.numeric()
auroc_value_hum_temp <- as.numeric()
set.seed(100)
training_folds <- createFolds(y=training_set[,6],k=10)

for(i in 1:10){
    fold_cv_test <- training_set[training_folds[[i]],] 
    fold_cv_train <- training_set[-training_folds[[i]],] 
    trained_model_hum_temp <- glm(Occupancy  ~ HumidityRatio + Temperature, data = fold_cv_train, family = binomial)
    pred_prob_hum_temp <- predict(trained_model_hum_temp, fold_cv_test, type='response')
    
    glm.pred <- rep(1,dim(fold_cv_test)[1])
    glm.pred[pred_prob_hum_temp<.5] <- 0
    accuracy_fold <- mean(glm.pred == fold_cv_test$Occupancy)
    accuracy_value <- append(accuracy_value, accuracy_fold)

    pr_hum_temp <- prediction(pred_prob_hum_temp, fold_cv_test$Occupancy)
    auroc_hum_temp <- performance(pr_hum_temp, measure = "auc")
    auroc_hum_temp <- auroc_hum_temp@y.values[[1]]
    auroc_value_hum_temp<- append(auroc_value_hum_temp,auroc_hum_temp)
    
}
cat('average accuracy value: ', mean(accuracy_value))
average accuracy value:  0.855
cat('average AUROC value: ', mean(auroc_value_hum_temp))
average AUROC value:  0.8718627

(e) Compare the performance of those three different models on predicting the testing dataset. Draw ROC curves for all individual models and calculating the corresponding AUROC values.

# Train the three models
trained_model_1 <- glm(Occupancy  ~ Temperature, data = training_set, family = binomial)
trained_model_2 <- glm(Occupancy  ~ HumidityRatio, data = training_set, family = binomial) 
trained_model_3 <- glm(Occupancy  ~ Temperature+HumidityRatio, data = training_set, family = binomial) 

prediction_trained_model_1 <- predict(trained_model_1, testing_set, type='response')
prediction_trained_model_2 <- predict(trained_model_2, testing_set, type='response')
prediction_trained_model_3 <- predict(trained_model_3, testing_set, type='response')

pr_trained_model_1 <- prediction(prediction_trained_model_1, testing_set$Occupancy)
pr_trained_model_2 <- prediction(prediction_trained_model_2, testing_set$Occupancy)
pr_trained_model_3 <- prediction(prediction_trained_model_3, testing_set$Occupancy)

# Calculate the AUROC values obtained by different models.
auroc_trained_model_1 <- performance(pr_trained_model_1, measure = "auc")
auroc_trained_model_2 <- performance(pr_trained_model_2, measure = "auc")
auroc_trained_model_3 <- performance(pr_trained_model_3, measure = "auc")
auroc_trained_model_value_1 <- auroc_trained_model_1@y.values[[1]]
auroc_trained_model_value_2 <- auroc_trained_model_2@y.values[[1]]
auroc_trained_model_value_3 <- auroc_trained_model_3@y.values[[1]]

# Get the True positive rate and False positive rate
prf_trained_model_1 <- performance(pr_trained_model_1, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
prf_trained_model_2 <- performance(pr_trained_model_2, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
prf_trained_model_3 <- performance(pr_trained_model_3, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
# Plot findings
plot(prf_trained_model_1, col="blue")
plot(prf_trained_model_2, col="orange", add=TRUE)
plot(prf_trained_model_3, col="red", add=TRUE)
legend(0.25,0.25, c(text=sprintf('AUROC(Temperature) = %s',round(auroc_trained_model_value_1, digits=3)),
text=sprintf('AUROC(HumidityRatio) = %s',round(auroc_trained_model_value_2, digits=3)),
text=sprintf('AUROC(HumidityRatio + Temperature) = %s',round(auroc_trained_model_value_3, digits=3))),
lty=1, cex=0.9, col = c("blue", "orange", "red"), bty="n", y.intersp=1, inset=c(0.1,-0.15))

We can see that Temperature is a better predictor for Occupancy as it has a higher true positive rate than HumidityRatio. Combining the two predictors does increase accuracy, however it is a minimal increase.
